-before-cutting/">Dress with Separately Cut Cups <span>(15)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="19"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-introductory-tutorial/">Bodysuit with Corset Cups <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong>Dressmaker’s Treasury will equip you with a range of necessary tools and techniques which every professional must possess for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>It will help you get more confident. You will know how to: </strong></p><ul><li>Choose the right strategy for making a garment after your first meeting with the client;</li><li>Take necessary measurements correctly and prepare and fill out an order form;</li><li>Choose the right basic pattern and adjust it after your client’s measurements with the help of automatic pattern adjustments calculation tables;</li><li>Avoid common mistakes which result in ill-fitting necklines by choosing the right sewing technique.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;5h 16m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-23-corset-back/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-23-corset-back/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-12-02T13:09:01+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-12-02T13:09:01+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 23. Corset Back."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 23. Corset Back."><meta itemprop="description" content="how to choose the right pattern for the front of your corset and now we can move to the back. Constructing the back of a corset is actually a lot easier"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 23. Corset Back.</h1><p><strong>We have talked about how to choose the right pattern for the front of your corset and now we can move to the back. </strong>Constructing the back of a corset is actually a lot easier although it does involve certain peculiarities.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2023.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I will highlight several aspects which require your attention. </strong></p><p>The first aspect is back neckline depth and its construction.</p><p>Another thing is how the back of your corset is laced: the edges may be laced together edge-to-edge or have a V-shaped gap between them.</p><p>And, finally, there are shoulder or halter straps which can either be cut one piece with the corset or cut separately after the back pattern of a corset with shoulders.</p><p><strong>Now let us go through all these aspects one by one. </strong></p><p>There are no fixed rules as to how you should choose the pattern of the back. All back patterns included in my courses are very similar to each other.</p><p><strong>The back of a corset normally consists of four parts: </strong>two centre back pieces and two side back pieces. There are rare cases when it is made of six parts.</p><p>It is up to you whether you want to make a four-part or a six-part back.</p><p><strong>The key rule is to keep the top edge at least 1cm below the shoulder blade level.</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2023.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It is very important and you must account for it when taking measurements. </strong></p><p>You find your client’s shoulder blade line (you can use an elastic band to mark it), step 1cm down from it, and mark the supposed top edge of the back of your garment.</p><p>If you need to make a high back neckline, then make sure the top edge goes at least 1cm above the shoulder blade level.</p><p>If you neglect this rule, the top edge of the back will cause discomfort to the wearer and affect the appearance of the corset in a negative way.</p><p><strong>There is another important moment I want to discuss with you.</strong></p><p><strong>There is a certain rule you must follow when you want to make a low-back corset and at the same time preserve good body-control properties.</strong></p><p><strong>The body-control properties will be preserved if the lowest point of the back neckline is positioned at least 8cm above waistline. </strong></p><p><strong>The closer to the waistline it is, the more the body-control properties degrade. </strong>This happens because there is not enough fabric at the back of the corset to re-shape the body.</p><p><strong>Thus if your goal is to improve your client’s figure and she is asking for a back neckline plunging nearly right to the waistline, then you can forget about the body-control effect and graceful curves! </strong>And you must absolutely warn your client about it.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2023.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>As sad as it is, you often have to refuse the client’s wish to have a dress or a corset with a low back neckline if she has a column body shape, </strong>i.e. narrow hips and wide waist with no defined transition between them. What to do, some women have a body shape like this although they may be quite slender at the same time.</p><p>A classic corset with a modest back neckline will re-shape a body like this in a nice way, highlight the waist, and form graceful curves. You must warn your client that she will not get the beautiful hourglass silhouette if she insists on a low back. Something has to be sacrificed: either your back is revealed almost down to the waistline but your body has an obvious column shape, or your back neckline stops 8cm above the waistline but you have a great silhouette!</p><p><strong>Let me give you some advice on how to make a low back for a corset in an easy and accurate way. </strong></p><p>You have at hand a basic pattern of a corset back included in all my courses.</p><p><strong>Of course, you can design a corset back of any desired shape on paper using this pattern as a foundation: </strong>just put the parts together and draw the common uninterrupted outline. But it is very hard to draw the transition between separate parts of the back in the princess seam areas, particularly if your client has a non-standard figure and you applied adjustments to the princess seams after doing relevant calculations. You are very likely to make a mistake because it is simply impossible to take everything in account!</p><p><strong>And this is why I always recommend working with mock-ups. </strong></p><p><strong>Customize the standard pattern</strong> by doing all necessary calculations and applying adjustments to all pieces including the back without worrying about the shape of the back neckline yet. Do everything as if you were going to make a plain high back neckline. <strong>Then sew a mock-up after the customized pattern. </strong></p><p><strong>Next, put the mock-up on the client, draw the desired back neckline shape right on her, and cut along the new line. </strong></p><p><strong>This is the easiest and most accurate way to make a well-fitting back neckline! </strong>But you will probably still have to make further adjustments and improve it.</p><p><strong>Most adjustments concern the princess seam areas of the back. </strong>When you trim the back of your mock-up corset on the client, the freshly cut neckline edge will not cling to the body. There will be some degree of looseness. This happens because the fabric was cut on the bias, which naturally makes it stretch out. You must remember about it and reinforce the bias-cut edge. It is a purely technical issue. During the fitting, take in the princess seams by a couple of millimeters to ensure a snug fit along the back with regard to your client’s anatomy.</p><p><strong>Let us also look at the opposite case when you need to make the back neckline higher than on the standard pattern. </strong></p><p><strong>Again, the mock-up method is the best. </strong>It is a tried and true method which minimizes the risk of errors. To tell you the truth, it is my favorite method because we work with tight-fit garments and not all things can be calculated mathematically because every figure is unique.</p><p><strong>Besides, many women have asymmetric bodies. </strong>Even minor spinal curvature and minor difference in shoulder height become very obvious at the back of a corset garment. When you are working with a mock-up and the client is standing in front of you, you can see certain things you would have likely missed out on paper.</p><p><strong>In order to make the back neckline higher, you must first of all lengthen the back pieces. </strong></p><p><strong>I have made a schematic drawing of the centre back piece and the side back piece on the writing board. </strong>You can also see the waistline with notches.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2023.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p>First of all, draw vertical lines going up from the waistline and through the top points of the back pieces.</p><p><strong>Drawing the armscye line of the side back piece is a little complicated. </strong>You know your client’s Width Back. Divide it in half, erase the seam allowance lines, and mark down section C-D, which is ½ of Width Back, and section A-B, which can be measured directly on the pattern.</p><p><strong>Then, mark the desired back length up from the waistline, add a seam allowance, trim accordingly – and here is roughly what your back pattern looks like!</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2023.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Then you can sew a mock-up after the new pattern and shape the back neckline right on it!</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2023.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I believe I have managed to show you that the mock-up method is the best for such work! </strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Boat-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20strapless.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Strapless Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20V%20neck.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> V-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/corset%20-%20neck%20strap.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Corset with Halter-Neck Strap</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/corset%20-%20shoulder%20strap.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/c